Therefore, I think the correct answer is 48.48 microns. **Final Answer** The separation between the two images in the focal plane is \boxed{48.48} microns. </think> To determine how far apart the images of two astronomical objects separated by 1 arc second will be in the focal plane of a telescope with an effective focal length of 10 meters, we start by converting the angular separation from arc seconds to radians. 1. **Convert 1 arc second to radians:** \[ 1 \text{ arc second} = \frac{1}{3600} \text{ degrees} = \frac{1}{3600} \times \frac{\pi}{180} \text{ radians} = \frac{\pi}{648000} \text{ radians} \approx 4.8481368 \times 10^{-6} \text{ radians} \] 2. **Calculate the linear separation in the focal plane:** \[ s = \theta \times f \] where \(\theta\) is the angular separation in radians and \(f\) is the focal length in meters. Substituting the values: \[ s = 4.8481368 \times 10^{-6} \text{ radians} \times 10 \text{ meters} \] \[ s \approx 4.8481368 \times 10^{-5} \text{ meters} \] 3. **Convert the linear separation from meters to microns:** \[ 1 \text{ meter} = 1,000,000 \text{ microns} \] \[ s \approx 4.8481368 \times 10^{-5} \text{ meters} \times 1,000,000 \text{ microns/meter} = 48.481368 \text{ microns} \] Rounding to two decimal places, the separation between the two images in the focal plane is approximately: \[ \boxed{48.48} \]microns.
